post_text:
Enrollment/orientation dates:
Junior High (grades 7-8)
7th grade students and parents should attend 7th grade Orientation at 9:00 a.m. on Friday, August 14. Students will receive their schedule and locker number at that time.
8th grade students can pick up a copy of their course schedule Friday, August 14 from 1:00 - 3:00 p.m.
High School (grades 9-12)
Seniors may select lockers and pick up a copy of their schedules Wednesday, August 12 from 9:00 - 11:00 a.m.
Juniors may select lockers and pick up a copy of their schedules Wednesday, August 12 from 1:00 - 3:00 p.m.
Sophomores may select lockers and pick up a copy of their schedules Thursday, August 13 from 9:00 - 11:00 a.m.
Freshmen and parents should attend Freshman Orientation at 1:00 p.m. on Thursday, August 13. Students will receive their schedule and can select a locker at that time.
Enrollment for students to attend virtually ends Friday August 14th.

Senior Spotlight. Tyler Guerin

Tyler is going to start off at State Fair and finish his schooling at Washburn University where he can obtain his degree in Radiation Therapy.

My parents have had a big impact in my life. They have showed me what kind of people I want in my life. They have taught me to pursue my goals and passions. They have taught me that anything worth having takes hard work.

Three things Tyler aspires to do in life is get in a cage with sharks, skydive, and take parents on a trip to Norway.

post_text:
Dear Parents and Community,

Due to heat and weather possibilities, graduation and baccalaureate have been moved indoors. Luckily the situation regarding the restrictions of seating has slightly eased. To provide enough distancing as well as seating at these ceremonies, each graduate will have 6 chairs set together designated for their family. (The drawing for these groups will occur at the beginning of graduation practice.)

Practice starts at 2pm on Saturday; make sure you are early. At graduation anyone “extra” not in your 6 chair family group will be in the open seating in the bleachers. There is no limit in the bleachers; however, social distancing in the bleachers is advised. Masks at graduation are encouraged.

post_text:
Osceola Public Schools will be holding SUMMER SCHOOL.

The dates for Summer School will be July 20th-31st, Monday thru Friday 8:00am-2:30pm with limited highway route bus transportation.
We will be running an on-site in class summer school with safety and sanitizing precautions in place. Due to some of the guidelines at this current time there will be a MAX of 12 students per classroom. Elementary classes from K-6 and 1/2 credit high school classes of Personal Finance, Health, Math, Foods and Credit Recovery will be offered.

ENROLLMENT will begin June 22nd and we will put the enrollment form on our school website and Facebook page. Parents will be notified when the enrollment form is ready by our text notification system.

If you have any questions you can email Dr. McClimans at cmcclimans@osceola.k12.mo.us or call 646-8333.

My plans after high school are to attend Mizzou and major in Forensic Anthropology. Working with dead bodies seems more fitting as they won’t talk back. I already moved to Columbia and can’t wait to start the next phase of my life….with faster internet!

Throughout high school, I participated in many extra curricular activities as well as working as a pharmacy technician. I also competed on competitive cheer and dance teams at Cheers!

My favorite part of high school was spending time with my friends and going to concerts.

I want to thank Mrs. Woods, Mr. L, and Ms. Foltz for all of your support!

The Osceola School District will participate in the Be The Light campaign. May 15th will be the final night. On Friday at 8:20pm(20:20 military time). We will turn on the lights at the football field to show support for the Class of 2020 and spring athletes, extra curricular participants, coaches, sponsors, and families. Seniors signs will be out about the football field.

The lights will be a symbol, showing that we are thinking of them and that eventually, we will return to school and competition.

The lights will be on for 20 minutes, starting at 8:20 p.m. You are invited to drive past the field and honk your horns or park around the field. We plan to announce the names of our graduating seniors each night. Please remain in your vehicles in order to adhere to physical distancing guidelines. #bethelight

Senior Spotlight.
HUNTER NOAKES :
I will be beginning an electrical lineman apprenticeship this fall for four years. I am very excited to begin the apprenticeship.
Yes, my apprenticeship will be in Kansas City and from there they can send me where ever need be.

I would like to thank my mom and dad for always believing in me and supporting me in everything. Not one time where they not there for me. They have always pushed me to be the best that I can be. Thank you mom and dad.
My favorite memory/memories at Osceola High School is playing football and going to weights with my buddies. There is nothing like playing football on a Friday night with your brothers. I’ll forever cherish the memories I have made at Osceola School. I am going to miss making memories at the school, and getting to talk to the staff but I am ready for the next chapter of my life. Thank you Osceola for everything you have done for me and my future.

post_text:
Senior Spotlight.
Elizabeth Garlick:
Hi! I’m Elizabeth and I like warm hugs! Just kidding we’re in quarantine! Anyway! I will be attending Northwest Missouri State University where I will receive my Bachelors of Science degree in marine biology. I have been involved in many school activities such as Student Council, FBLA, NHS, FCCLA, choir, band, Strength Club, track and field, volleyball, and softball. I have quite a few hobbies that include: singing in the shower and to my cat, laughing with my sisters, stressing about homework lol, and hanging with my friends! As you can see I have had a pretty great life here at Osceola and even though my last year has been cut short I couldn’t be any more grateful for the life experiences and the memories I have gained! The teachers and staff, my friends and family have all been so supportive and loving. All I have left to say is thank you Osceola for everything you have taught me!

post_text:
Senior Spotlight.

Kaylee Pipes:

My name is Kaylee Pipes. I have been involved in FCCLA all four years of highschool where I have served as Chapter Membership Representative and Chapter President two consecutive years as well as serving as Regional Historian and Regional President throughout my four years. I competed in many events where I earned gold medals and made it to Nationals the three years that I could. I also attended the National Cluster Meetings and earned 3rd place in Interview Skills and 1st place in the nation in Science in FCS. I was also involved in yearbook, cheer, and softball. I also am currently employed at the St. Clair County Library. My plans for after highschool are to attend State Fair Community College. My ultimate goal is to get an Associate's Degree in Healthcare Management and a Master's Degree in Business Administration. My ultimate job goal is to become a director in the hospital environment. My mom inspired this job career and I am so excited for this next chapter in my life!

The Osceola School District will participate in the Be The Light campaign on Friday, April 10th at 8:20pm. We will turn on the lights at the football field to show support for the Class of 2020 and spring athletes, extra curricular participants, coaches, sponsors, and families.

The lights will be a symbol, showing that we are thinking of them and that eventually, we will return to school and competition.

The lights will be on for 20 minutes, starting at 8:20 p.m. You are invited to drive past the field and honk your horns. Please remain in your vehicles in order to adhere to physical distancing guidelines.

Due to health officials recommending cancelling group gatherings and social distancing for health reasons due to COVID-19, school and all activities are postponed thru April 3. Mike Fransen, Superintendent

post_text: Parents as Teachers will be offering a FREE Developmental Screening on March 5, 2020, for children in the Osceola School District, that will be age 4 by August 1st. If you are interested in enrolling your kiddo for Preschool (4 year old) in the Fall your child will need a screening. There are available screening times from 8-11:30 AM. If you have not already been contacted to make an appointment, please call 646-8333 ext 239 and make an appointment as soon as possible. Parents as Teachers also has screening openings for children 4 months up to age 3.
